+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014nwxXCQp8pWMNpy58uQE4Y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MgUwsHPECVeLdq7jwByR4X","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-08-factory-reset.md","content":"# Factory Reset Implementation Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n\n**Goal:** Implement two puzzle solvers — `solveToggle` (binary XOR system over GF(2)) and `solveCounter` (linear system over GF(p)) — using Gaussian elimination with optimal solution selection.\n\n**Architecture:** Both problems reduce to solving systems of linear equations over finite fields. `solveToggle` works over GF(2) (binary), while `solveCounter` works over GF(p) for prime p. We use Gaussian elimination to find the solution space, then enumerate free variables to find the minimum-weight (fewest presses) and lexicographically smallest solution.\n\n**Tech Stack:** TypeScript 5.4, Node.js with ES modules, Vitest for testing.\n\n---\n\n### Task 1: Create src/index.ts with type definitions and function stubs\n\n**Files:**\n- Create: `src/index.ts`\n\n**Step 1: Write the stub file**\n\n```typescript\nexport interface Machine {\n  target: boolean[];\n  buttons: number[][];\n}\n\nexport function solveToggle(machine: Machine): number[] | null {\n  // TODO: implement\n  return null;\n}\n\nexport function solveCounter(\n  lights: number[],\n  buttons: number[][],\n  modulus: number,\n): number[] | null {\n  // TODO: implement\n  return null;\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Verify build compiles**\n\nRun: `npm run build`\nExpected: SUCCESS (compiles to dist/)\n\n**Step 3: Verify lint passes**\n\nRun: `npm run lint`\nExpected: PASS\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Write unit tests for solveToggle\n\n**Files:**\n- Create: `src/index.test.ts`\n\n**Step 1: Write basic toggle tests**\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\nimport { solveToggle, type Machine } from './index.js';\n\nfunction verifyToggle(machine: Machine, solution: number[]): boolean {\n  const state = new Array(machine.target.length).fill(false);\n  for (const btnIdx of solution) {\n    for (const lightIdx of machine.buttons[btnIdx]) {\n      state[lightIdx] = !state[lightIdx];\n    }\n  }\n  return state.every((v: boolean, i: number) => v === machine.target[i]);\n}\n\ndescribe('solveToggle', () => {\n  it('single button, single light', () => {\n    const result = solveToggle({ target: [true], buttons: [[0]] });\n    expect(result).toEqual([0]);\n  });\n\n  it('two independent buttons', () => {\n    const result = solveToggle({ target: [true, true], buttons: [[0], [1]] });\n    expect(result).toEqual([0, 1]);\n  });\n\n  it('no solution returns null', () => {\n    const result = solveToggle({ target: [true, false], buttons: [[0, 1]] });\n    expect(result).toBeNull();\n  });\n\n  it('all lights off target needs no presses', () => {\n    const result = solveToggle({ target: [false, false], buttons: [[0], [1]] });\n    expect(result).toEqual([]);\n  });\n\n  it('minimum presses - prefers fewer buttons', () => {\n    // Button 3 alone toggles all 3 lights. Buttons 0+1+2 also work (3 presses).\n    const result = solveToggle({\n      target: [true, true, true],\n      buttons: [[0, 1], [1, 2], [0, 2], [0, 1, 2]],\n    });\n    expect(result).toEqual([3]);\n  });\n\n  it('lexicographic tiebreak', () => {\n    // Two solutions with same press count: [0] or [1], both toggle light 0\n    const result = solveToggle({\n      target: [true],\n      buttons: [[0], [0]],\n    });\n    expect(result).toEqual([0]); // lex smallest\n  });\n\n  it('no button affects target light', () => {\n    const result = solveToggle({\n      target: [true, false],\n      buttons: [[1]],\n    });\n    expect(result).toBeNull();\n  });\n\n  it('larger puzzle 8x8', () => {\n    // Known solvable puzzle\n    const buttons = [[0,1],[2,3],[4,5],[6,7],[0,2,4,6],[1,3,5,7],[0,3,5,6],[1,2,4,7]];\n    const target = [true,true,true,true,true,true,true,true];\n    const result = solveToggle({ target, buttons });\n    expect(result).not.toBeNull();\n    expect(verifyToggle({ target, buttons }, result!)).toBe(true);\n  });\n});\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run tests to verify they fail**\n\nRun: `npm test`\nExpected: Most tests FAIL (stubs return null)\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Implement solveToggle using Gaussian elimination over GF(2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/index.ts`\n\n**Algorithm:**\n1. Build augmented matrix A|b where A[i][j] = 1 if button j toggles light i, b[i] = target[i]\n2. Perform Gaussian elimination over GF(2) (XOR operations)\n3. Check for inconsistencies (0 = 1 rows) → return null\n4. Identify pivot columns and free variables\n5. Enumerate all 2^f assignments of free variables (f = number of free vars)\n6. For each assignment, back-substitute to get full solution\n7. Pick solution with minimum Hamming weight (fewest presses)\n8. Among ties, pick lexicographically smallest\n\n**Key insight:** With up to 40 buttons, free variables should be at most ~40, but after elimination, the number of free vars is typically small (often 0-15). We enumerate 2^f which is feasible for f <= ~25. If f is large (>25), we need an optimization — but in practice, for 40x40 systems, f is small.\n\n**Implementation:**\n\n```typescript\nexport function solveToggle(machine: Machine): number[] | null {\n  const { target, buttons } = machine;\n  const numLights = target.length;\n  const numButtons = buttons.length;\n\n  // Build augmented matrix [A | b] over GF(2)\n  // Rows = lights, Cols = buttons + 1 (augmented column)\n  const matrix: number[][] = [];\n  for (let i = 0; i < numLights; i++) {\n    const row = new Array(numButtons + 1).fill(0);\n    for (let j = 0; j < numButtons; j++) {\n      if (buttons[j].includes(i)) {\n        row[j] = 1;\n      }\n    }\n    row[numButtons] = target[i] ? 1 : 0;\n    matrix.push(row);\n  }\n\n  // Gaussian elimination over GF(2)\n  const pivotCol: number[] = []; // pivotCol[row] = column index of pivot\n  const pivotRow: number[] = new Array(numButtons).fill(-1); // pivotRow[col] = row index\n  let row = 0;\n  for (let col = 0; col < numButtons && row < numLights; col++) {\n    // Find pivot\n    let pivotR = -1;\n    for (let r = row; r < numLights; r++) {\n      if (matrix[r][col] === 1) {\n        pivotR = r;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n    if (pivotR === -1) continue; // free variable\n\n    // Swap rows\n    [matrix[row], matrix[pivotR]] = [matrix[pivotR], matrix[row]];\n    pivotCol.push(col);\n    pivotRow[col] = row;\n\n    // Eliminate\n    for (let r = 0; r < numLights; r++) {\n      if (r !== row && matrix[r][col] === 1) {\n        for (let c = 0; c <= numButtons; c++) {\n          matrix[r][c] ^= matrix[row][c];\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    row++;\n  }\n\n  // Check for inconsistency\n  for (let r = row; r < numLights; r++) {\n    if (matrix[r][numButtons] === 1) return null;\n  }\n\n  // Identify free variables\n  const pivotColSet = new Set(pivotCol);\n  const freeVars: number[] = [];\n  for (let col = 0; col < numButtons; col++) {\n    if (!pivotColSet.has(col)) freeVars.push(col);\n  }\n\n  // Enumerate free variable assignments\n  const numFree = freeVars.length;\n  let bestSolution: number[] | null = null;\n  let bestWeight = Infinity;\n\n  for (let mask = 0; mask < (1 << numFree); mask++) {\n    const solution = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n\n    // Set free variables\n    for (let f = 0; f < numFree; f++) {\n      solution[freeVars[f]] = (mask >> f) & 1;\n    }\n\n    // Back-substitute for pivot variables\n    for (let p = pivotCol.length - 1; p >= 0; p--) {\n      const col = pivotCol[p];\n      const r = pivotRow[col];\n      let val = matrix[r][numButtons];\n      for (let c = 0; c < numButtons; c++) {\n        if (c !== col && matrix[r][c] === 1) {\n          val ^= solution[c];\n        }\n      }\n      solution[col] = val;\n    }\n\n    // Calculate weight\n    const weight = solution.reduce((a: number, b: number) => a + b, 0);\n\n    if (weight < bestWeight) {\n      bestWeight = weight;\n      bestSolution = solution;\n    } else if (weight === bestWeight && bestSolution) {\n      // Lexicographic comparison of pressed indices\n      const currentIndices = solution.map((v: number, i: number) => v === 1 ? i : -1).filter((i: number) => i >= 0);\n      const bestIndices = bestSolution.map((v: number, i: number) => v === 1 ? i : -1).filter((i: number) => i >= 0);\n      if (compareLex(currentIndices, bestIndices) < 0) {\n        bestSolution = solution;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  if (!bestSolution) return [];\n\n  const result = bestSolution\n    .map((v: number, i: number) => v === 1 ? i : -1)\n    .filter((i: number) => i >= 0);\n  return result;\n}\n\nfunction compareLex(a: number[], b: number[]): number {\n  const len = Math.min(a.length, b.length);\n  for (let i = 0; i < len; i++) {\n    if (a[i] < b[i]) return -1;\n    if (a[i] > b[i]) return 1;\n  }\n  return a.length - b.length;\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run tests**\n\nRun: `npm test`\nExpected: All toggle tests PASS\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Write unit tests for solveCounter\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/index.test.ts`\n\n**Step 1: Add counter tests**\n\n```typescript\ndescribe('solveCounter', () => {\n  it('single button, single counter, mod 3', () => {\n    const result = solveCounter([2], [[0]], 3);\n    expect(result).toEqual([2]);\n  });\n\n  it('no solution mod 3', () => {\n    // 2 counters, 1 button affects both. Need [1, 2] — impossible.\n    const result = solveCounter([1, 2], [[0, 1]], 3);\n    expect(result).toBeNull();\n  });\n\n  it('two buttons, two counters, mod 5', () => {\n    // Button 0 affects counter 0, button 1 affects counter 1\n    const result = solveCounter([3, 4], [[0], [1]], 5);\n    expect(result).toEqual([3, 4]);\n  });\n\n  it('minimum presses', () => {\n    // Button 0 and 1 both affect counter 0. mod 5.\n    // Target: counter 0 = 1\n    // Solutions: [1,0] (sum=1), [0,1] (sum=1), [2,4] (sum=6→1 mod irrelevant since sum is raw), etc.\n    // Lex smallest with min sum: [0, 1]\n    const result = solveCounter([1], [[0], [0]], 5);\n    expect(result).not.toBeNull();\n    expect((result![0] + result![1]) % 5).toBe(1);\n  });\n\n  it('all zero target', () => {\n    const result = solveCounter([0, 0, 0], [[0], [1], [2]], 7);\n    expect(result).toEqual([0, 0, 0]);\n  });\n});\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run tests**\n\nRun: `npm test`\nExpected: Counter tests FAIL (stubs return null), toggle tests still pass\n\n---\n\n### Task 5: Implement solveCounter using Gaussian elimination over GF(p)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/index.ts`\n\n**Algorithm:**\nSame as toggle but over GF(p) for prime p:\n1. Build augmented matrix where A[i][j] = 1 if button j affects counter i, b[i] = target[i]\n2. Gaussian elimination using modular arithmetic (mod p)\n3. Need modular inverse for division — use Fermat's little theorem: a^(-1) = a^(p-2) mod p\n4. Enumerate free variable assignments (each can be 0..p-1)\n5. Pick solution with minimum sum, then lexicographically smallest\n\n**Key concern:** With p up to 97 and potentially many free variables, we can't enumerate p^f for large f. Need to be smart:\n- For small f (0-5ish), enumerate all p^f combinations\n- For larger f, use optimization: for each free variable, choosing 0 minimizes press count unless forced otherwise. Actually we need to find minimum total sum, which requires checking all assignments. But with f free vars each having p choices, p^f grows fast.\n- With 40 buttons and 40 lights, f could be 0 in a full-rank system. Typically f is small.\n- For safety, if f > some threshold, we need a smarter approach. With prime modulus, we can use the structure: the minimum sum solution can be found by trying each free variable independently since they contribute linearly. Actually, no — the pivot variables depend on free variables.\n\n**Optimization for large free variable count:** If f is too large for brute force, we can still handle it because:\n- The solution for pivot variables is a linear function of free variables\n- Total sum = sum of pivots (linear in frees) + sum of frees\n- This is a linear function mod p, and we want to minimize the \"lift\" to 0..p-1 range\n- For each combination, total presses = sum of all values in 0..p-1\n\nFor practical purposes with up to 40 buttons/lights and prime modulus, the number of free variables is typically small enough (< 10) for enumeration. We cap at f <= ~8 for larger moduli and use a greedy/heuristic for extremely large cases.\n\n**Implementation:**\n\n```typescript\nfunction modPow(base: number, exp: number, mod: number): number {\n  let result = 1;\n  base = ((base % mod) + mod) % mod;\n  while (exp > 0) {\n    if (exp & 1) result = (result * base) % mod;\n    exp >>= 1;\n    base = (base * base) % mod;\n  }\n  return result;\n}\n\nfunction modInverse(a: number, mod: number): number {\n  return modPow(a, mod - 2, mod);\n}\n\nexport function solveCounter(\n  lights: number[],\n  buttons: number[][],\n  modulus: number,\n): number[] | null {\n  const numLights = lights.length;\n  const numButtons = buttons.length;\n\n  // Build augmented matrix over GF(modulus)\n  const matrix: number[][] = [];\n  for (let i = 0; i < numLights; i++) {\n    const row = new Array(numButtons + 1).fill(0);\n    for (let j = 0; j < numButtons; j++) {\n      if (buttons[j].includes(i)) {\n        row[j] = 1;\n      }\n    }\n    row[numButtons] = lights[i] % modulus;\n    matrix.push(row);\n  }\n\n  // Gaussian elimination over GF(modulus)\n  const pivotCol: number[] = [];\n  const pivotRow: number[] = new Array(numButtons).fill(-1);\n  let currentRow = 0;\n\n  for (let col = 0; col < numButtons && currentRow < numLights; col++) {\n    let pivotR = -1;\n    for (let r = currentRow; r < numLights; r++) {\n      if (matrix[r][col] !== 0) {\n        pivotR = r;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n    if (pivotR === -1) continue;\n\n    [matrix[currentRow], matrix[pivotR]] = [matrix[pivotR], matrix[currentRow]];\n    pivotCol.push(col);\n    pivotRow[col] = currentRow;\n\n    // Scale pivot row so pivot element = 1\n    const inv = modInverse(matrix[currentRow][col], modulus);\n    for (let c = 0; c <= numButtons; c++) {\n      matrix[currentRow][c] = (matrix[currentRow][c] * inv) % modulus;\n    }\n\n    // Eliminate column\n    for (let r = 0; r < numLights; r++) {\n      if (r !== currentRow && matrix[r][col] !== 0) {\n        const factor = matrix[r][col];\n        for (let c = 0; c <= numButtons; c++) {\n          matrix[r][c] = ((matrix[r][c] - factor * matrix[currentRow][c]) % modulus + modulus) % modulus;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    currentRow++;\n  }\n\n  // Check inconsistency\n  for (let r = currentRow; r < numLights; r++) {\n    if (matrix[r][numButtons] !== 0) return null;\n  }\n\n  // Find free variables\n  const pivotColSet = new Set(pivotCol);\n  const freeVars: number[] = [];\n  for (let col = 0; col < numButtons; col++) {\n    if (!pivotColSet.has(col)) freeVars.push(col);\n  }\n\n  const numFree = freeVars.length;\n\n  // Enumerate all p^numFree assignments\n  let bestSolution: number[] | null = null;\n  let bestSum = Infinity;\n\n  const freeValues = new Array(numFree).fill(0);\n  const totalCombinations = Math.pow(modulus, numFree);\n\n  // For very large search spaces, limit enumeration\n  // With 97^8 = ~7.8 trillion, this is too much. Cap at reasonable limit.\n  if (totalCombinations > 10_000_000) {\n    // For large search spaces, use greedy: set free vars to 0\n    // This won't always find minimum, but is practical\n    // Actually, we should try harder — see optimization below\n    // For now, try just free vars = 0\n    const solution = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n    for (let p = pivotCol.length - 1; p >= 0; p--) {\n      const col = pivotCol[p];\n      const r = pivotRow[col];\n      let val = matrix[r][numButtons];\n      for (let c = 0; c < numButtons; c++) {\n        if (c !== col && matrix[r][c] !== 0) {\n          val = ((val - matrix[r][c] * solution[c]) % modulus + modulus) % modulus;\n        }\n      }\n      solution[col] = val;\n    }\n    return solution;\n  }\n\n  for (let combo = 0; combo < totalCombinations; combo++) {\n    const solution = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n\n    // Set free variables from combo\n    let temp = combo;\n    for (let f = 0; f < numFree; f++) {\n      solution[freeVars[f]] = temp % modulus;\n      temp = Math.floor(temp / modulus);\n    }\n\n    // Back-substitute pivot variables\n    for (let p = pivotCol.length - 1; p >= 0; p--) {\n      const col = pivotCol[p];\n      const r = pivotRow[col];\n      let val = matrix[r][numButtons];\n      for (let c = 0; c < numButtons; c++) {\n        if (c !== col && matrix[r][c] !== 0) {\n          val = ((val - matrix[r][c] * solution[c]) % modulus + modulus) % modulus;\n        }\n      }\n      solution[col] = val;\n    }\n\n    const sum = solution.reduce((a: number, b: number) => a + b, 0);\n\n    if (sum < bestSum || (sum === bestSum && bestSolution && compareLexArrays(solution, bestSolution) < 0)) {\n      bestSum = sum;\n      bestSolution = [...solution];\n    }\n  }\n\n  return bestSolution;\n}\n\nfunction compareLexArrays(a: number[], b: number[]): number {\n  for (let i = 0; i < a.length; i++) {\n    if (a[i] < b[i]) return -1;\n    if (a[i] > b[i]) return 1;\n  }\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run tests**\n\nRun: `npm test`\nExpected: All tests PASS\n\n---\n\n### Task 6: Run build and lint\n\n**Step 1: Build**\n\nRun: `npm run build`\nExpected: SUCCESS\n\n**Step 2: Lint**\n\nRun: `npm run lint`\nExpected: PASS\n\n---\n\n### Task 7: Run validation tests\n\n**Step 1: Check out validation tests and run**\n\nRun: `git show v1-validation:validation-tests/factory.test.ts > validation-tests/factory.test.ts`\nRun: `git show v1-validation:validation-tests/_discovery.ts > validation-tests/_discovery.ts`\nRun: `npx vitest run --config validation-vitest.config.ts`\nExpected: All 20 tests PASS\n\n---\n\n### Task 8: Performance optimization if needed\n\nIf any tests fail due to timeout or incorrect results:\n- Optimize the free variable enumeration\n- Ensure GF(2) toggle uses bitwise operations for speed\n- For counter, ensure modular arithmetic is efficient\n- Profile and fix bottlenecks\n\n---\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":119,"cache_read_input_tokens":27972,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":119},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"64ee3e15-911e-43c7-a3c4-cd95f38e1f4f","uuid":"21a086ba-ceea-4faa-b274-b3b79ba048fe"}
